Product Id: Annual Income Estimates for Census Families and Individuals (T1 Family File)

Longitudinal cohort analysis: Graduates of a given cohort are observed for a period of five years after graduation, although results are only shown for two and five years afterwards (for example, results for graduates of the calendar year 2010 are shown in 2012 and 2015). Graduates who had no income data or returned to school full time in any of the five years were excluded from the income analysis subpopulations for the entire five year period. This ensures that the income analysis subpopulations are the same in every year of analysis and the results can be compared over time. See the technical reference guide <a href=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/37-20-0001/372000012024001-eng.htm" rel="external noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Labour market outcomes for college and university graduates

Estimates may not be available for all reference periods for all geographies, due to data limitations. The Canada estimates exclude college graduates for the following provinces and territories and graduate cohorts: Ontario (2010 to 2013), New Brunswick (2010), Manitoba (2010), Territories (2010 and 2011).
Due to data limitations, estimates for the 2010 cohort are not available for New Brunswick college graduates.

Quebec CEGEP graduates with a diploma in the technical stream leading to labour market entry are included in the study population, while pre-university diploma graduates from CEGEPs are excluded. University micro-programs and attestations are excluded at the undergraduate, master's and doctoral levels.
Due to data limitations, estimates for the 2010 to 2013 cohorts are not available for Ontario college graduates.
Due to data limitations, estimates for the 2010 cohort are not available for Manitoba college graduates, nor for graduates who obtained Career

Product Id: The Territories include Yukon, the Northwest Territories, and Nunavut. Due to data limitations, estimates for the Territories are not available for the 2010 and 2011 graduate cohorts.

Educational qualification is derived by combining two Postsecondary Student Information System (PSIS) variables: program type and credential type. For consistency and homogeneity across provinces and territories, two adjustments are made. (1) Medicine, Dentistry, Veterinary medicine, Optometry, Pharmacy and Law degrees reported as Undergraduate degrees" or "Post-baccalaureate non-graduate degrees" are regrouped as "Professional degrees." (2) "Post-baccalaureate non-graduate degrees" in the fields of Education and Social work are regrouped with "Undergraduate degrees". <a href="http://www23.statcan.gc.ca/imdb/p3VD.pl?Function=getVD&TVD=1252576" rel="external noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Classification of programs and credentials - professional degree variant (opens new window)<a/>."
